sub: Earthbound if it was a F2P Mobile Game
com:
>If a member of your party dies, you can revive them by watching a video Ad
>The XP accumulation rate is 1/4 of the original game, but you can bring it back up by logging in 7 days in a row (or buying a pass)
>All music is replaced with royalty free orchestral scores
>Despite being able to revive as much as you want, the game walls you after Saturn Valley. The difficulty makes it nearly impossible to progress without spending real life currency or grinding for a few hundred hours
>Instead of having an overarching story, roughly halfway through the game it becomes a roguelike with no end
>Most of the game is oversexualized
>Getting goods from NPCs requires watching a video Ad or paying real life money
>Dead Multiplayer Combat area that takes forever to find a match within your skill level

Now think of all the great games that were never made because of the F2P monetization model

Well, my approach to writing things tends to start with just having a piano sketch! I write the melody, the chords, and the overall form from beginning to end on piano, and then start transferring things over to other instruments, depending on the style, and type of music! So like, you can have a melody on guitar, or chords on strings, or synths, or whatever! It's a sort of "start small, and develop things to get bigger" mindset though that I work with.

Layers get added in depending on what things are often needed. Once you have melody, chords, and form, I'll typically bring in percussion, which can be a huge part of a piece overall! Then I'll add a bass, and it can be an actual electric bass, or low strings, or trombone, or whatever! But it's a low melody line that re-enforcing the roots of the chords, and the progression you're on! One thing I like to do in particular though is write a counter-melody that sits slightly less importantly than the main melody line. This risks feeling busy, but that's where mixing, and panning can come into play. A main melody can be situated dead center, while a counter melody could be panned in the sides, so there's extra room.
